<subSubSection id="7458426A9716B8EF7C9B28568A204331" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="290F27550BA3E9C01560BE2EFDEC8641" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
57. 
<taxonomicName id="23A91622246E8A4E9DA8525C2F6A3772" LSID="EAC493EF-74AA-5A57-82E6-9DC15954154D" authority="R. W. Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson 2001: 12)." authorityName="R. W. Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson" authorityYear="2001" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus graminetinus" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="graminetinus">Convolvulus graminetinus R.W.Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson 2001: 12).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6ABF62B4E2DEF62207971B6AAE31AB49" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="type">
<paragraph id="70F32EE0B413D5DBE06EC69EB84FF36D" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="04A9A25DBAB0FF2197FBEB76F24F2548" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
AUSTRALIA, Queensland, 
<emphasis id="D6B6B39DF90D8F2FD94FE1FB33B736CC" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">R.W.Johnson</emphasis>
5300 (holotype BRI; isotypes CANB, K!, NE, NSW).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="55199AA9EB7F9B08CFD0BE55A24EF087" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph id="12EC5164931550E753D1F6EAD44110B8" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A3332EC6281FCAC45D28C95482DCD1A" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Perennial herb with trailing or twining stems to at least 50 cm, plant thinly pubescent to glabrescent. Leaves petiolate, dimorphic; petioles 2-10 mm; lowermost leaves 2.5-4 
<normalizedToken id="7C5D30BCCB6E2AB62553707632923573" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.6-1.6 cm, deltoid, obtuse and finely mucronate, entire, base truncate and briefly cuneate onto the petiole, auricles absent; middle leaves similar but base more or less cordate, auricles present, often bifid or tridentate, the central lobe longer and narrower; middle and upper leaves with a narrowly linear-lanceolate central lobe 3-6 
<normalizedToken id="E4A49B64A496A9ED74A5FCDE6F113C84" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.1-0. 6 cm, the basal auricles more or less reflexed so base sagittate, inconspicuous, bifid or trifid, 3-5 mm long, segments usually very narrow. Flowers solitary (very rarely paired), pedunculate, axillary; peduncles 1.2-3.5(-5.5) cm, recurved in fruit; bracteoles 1-2.5 mm, filiform; pedicels 4-12 mm; sepals 4-6 
<normalizedToken id="D4D5322D226D8FFD3EEC37E44700C380" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3 mm, obovate or elliptic, rounded and mucronate, scarious-margined, glabrous or pubescent on dorsal surface near apex; corolla 0.7-1.6 cm long, pink, shallowly lobed with triangular lobes, midpetaline bands pilose; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 3-4 mm above base, stigmas 1.5-2 mm. Capsule glabrous; seeds with prominent wavy tubercles. [
<bibRefCitation id="BD2092DED725BE02072F105C5B1F55DF" author="Johnson, RW" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="1 - 39" refId="B167" refString="Johnson, RW, 2001. A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia. Austrobaileya 6: 1 - 39" title="A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia." volume="6" year="2001">Johnson 2001</bibRefCitation>
: 12-14, figs3-4, map 2]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="80CAB48E0685007B474C255407001195" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C78AC1766EAFEEDF6C9E88A9DDF8C6F0" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15713D70E63E2C5EB9183CD3E9C7CEB3" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Australia: Northern Territory, Queensland and New South Wales (
<emphasis id="6580FE789F1D176EE9CF308C5013B52D" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Evans</emphasis>
3248, 
<emphasis id="2A9EDD0CCD2FBB7A79E99D0CDF306811" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Must</emphasis>
1510, 
<emphasis id="C379296AA86F5FB9E130628DF0E92A8D" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Johnson</emphasis>
2075, 
<emphasis id="ACC47142304252C01ECBDD3663390EF9" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Hubbard</emphasis>
3171, 
<emphasis id="F98A48954BFF2BBAA0FE07DDC118A274" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">McDonald</emphasis>
46, 
<emphasis id="1D7A97DEA2F73B4E22F9454117B5CC48" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Clemens</emphasis>
s.n. [9/1945], 
<emphasis id="E17068C1CC694F916A0FD3B05EC29FFE" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">McBarron</emphasis>
14875, 
<emphasis id="6EA149D046433FADE3E4C240CCBA065F" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Melville</emphasis>
3425). Reported from New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation id="B918292DF797ED00076439FDEA41AEE0" author="Heenan, PB" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="447 - 457" publicationUrl="10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" refId="B151" refString="Heenan, PB, Molloy, BPJ, de Lange, PJ, 2003. Species of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae)- endemic to New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Botany 41: 447 - 457, DOI: 10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" title="Species of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae) - endemic to New Zealand." url="10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" volume="41" year="2003">Heenan et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
) but possibly extinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="368FF519E21088DD029110C9B9F0B02F" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="notes">
<paragraph id="BAAB68B00BF2F745AF83E6BED4509BDC" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86402A699A56183203298252E9C28E59" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Very immature plants could be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="EA8A337670EDBB0C43DC027017753F5A" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis id="1320C91589B49A462890BA9DB68EF1C8" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the corolla is much smaller. More mature plants without lower leaves are similar morphologically to 
<taxonomicName id="4BCA4F9D40BEA015746F26E26EA703F9" authorityName="R. Br., Prodr. Fl. Nov. Holland 483. 1810. (Brown" authorityYear="1810" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus remotus" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis id="1FA11A03306F3F9A280F5C1F3A523067" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Convolvulus remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the fruiting peduncle is recurved. The strongly tuberculate seeds and the leaves with a very long narrow central lobe combined with the small bifid auricles are also rather distinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
